_IFgyXTLFRjaS5udTyi_9Gf0-Afpw]. They=E2=80=99ve already done the hard part =
of getting these heavy items to the edge, which Outfit piggybacks on.
To be clear, this is going to be difficult to pull off. No one has ever don=
e it before. As a general rule of thumb, architecture and construction don=
=E2=80=99t scale. But Outfit=E2=80=99s founder, Ian Janicki, has spent most=
 of his life building up the skills to change that.=C2=A0
Ian: Product-Founder Fit
Like most of the deals we do in the Not Boring Syndicate, Outfit is very ea=
rly stage. It=E2=80=99s a small team with an early product and a small batc=
h of customers in their Beta. At this very early stage, where company and i=
dea are one in the same, you=E2=80=99re betting on a few things:=C2=A0
The idea seems feasible.=C2=A0
The market is very big, or if the company is successful, it will create its=
 own big market.
The Founder(s).=C2=A0
Of these three, the Founder is the most important. The idea may change, and=
 the market may not even exist yet. If it does, it=E2=80=99s likely full of=
 unwelcoming incumbents looking to beat the new entrant out of business. A =
great Founder can overcome those obstacles, evolving the idea based on cust=
omer feedback while staying true to the vision, willing a market into being=
, and fighting for their big piece of it.=C2=A0
Ian Janicki is the perfect Founder for Outfit. A second-generation architec=
t, Ian grew up in the trades, working construction as a teenager before stu=
dying at the nation=E2=80=99s top undergrad architecture program, Cornell.=
=C2=A0
What the hell happened in 2015?!
While at Cornell, Ian learned how to engineer software as well as buildings=
=2E When he graduated, understanding tha=
t the path for a junior architect is =
a miserable one, he decided to head to San Francisco to try his hand at sof=
tware instead. Over the past eight years, he=E2=80=99s worked as a Product =
Designer and Product Manager at open source mobile-app platform Xamarin (ac=
quired by Microsoft), Microsoft, construction unicorn Katerra, and design u=
nicorn Figma (the very same software with which I make all my beautiful ima=
ges!).=C2=A0
He always knew that he wanted to get back into architecture, but not in the=
 traditional sense. Instead, he=E2=80=99s on a mission to make architecture=
 scale with software. Outfit is the manifestation of that mission, and of t=
he lessons he learned, particularly at Katerra.=C2=A0
Traditional architecture relies on teams of junior people to churn plan aft=
er drawing after plan after drawing. Pre-fab has high fixed costs in a cycl=
ical industry, tough labor arbitrage, and can=E2=80=99t reach economies of =
scale.=C2=A0
Ian=E2=80=99s first exploration to make the process easier was to build an =
API for building permits and inspections, which, if you=E2=80=99ve ever had=
 to deal with building permits and inspections is an absolute nightmare. Th=
e process requires in-person interaction across 20,000 separate jurisdictio=
ns with no standardization, no incentive to improve, and all of the fun tha=
t comes with dealing with local government. No go.=C2=A0
He then looked at existing models, like Made and Block and realized three t=
hings:
They=E2=80=99re difficult to scale.=C2=A0
They still need to deal with permitting.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99ve left a massive hole in the middle of the market.=C2=A0
Made and Block appeal to the segment of the market that is willing to spend=
 $30-50k to have someone else design and build beautiful bathrooms and kitc=
hens for them. But that=E2=80=99s a small piece of the overall market. Outf=
it is for the rest.=C2=A0
Target Customer and Marketing=C2=A0
One of my favorite slides I=E2=80=99ve ever seen in a pitch deck is Ian=E2=
=80=99s customer slide, in which he defines Outfit=E2=80=99s customer as:=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CA middle-class, suburban, young couple (not you).=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Often, companies whose products VCs can see using themselves have an easier=
 time fundraising than products that they can=E2=80=99t. It=E2=80=99s one o=
f the reasons that Airbnb [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUMtuxCAM_Jr=
lthGPhLIHDr30NyIHvAldAhGYVvn70t1DVcmWJY_t8YwDwjWX0x65EmsVyxy8FVoaNY035u3ohZ=
kMC3W-F8QdQrRUGrKjLTE4oJDTc4NzObHNmvvbbfLajAt4fXfa35QEJUcujVROA_vlmaH5gMmhx=
S8sZ07Iot2IjnpR7xf50YM2XDFhgRgqDbUtlcA9Bpf3Dh49IZQlLdc-d_WhQiUsVyjUp1mwkksu=
pOBCTW_KDGLIn9noZKJoj8vI91X-O8mKTZmWXEJaO_zYYMf4BLrKude9pUDnjAmWiP5lAL0se-q=
h80Cb8LtGpP7Iq9ldkaMwQhvNOpvP3bz0R_QDRw-Chg] had such a hard time raising m=
oney initially. What VC in their right mind would let a stranger stay in th=
eir house for a hundred bucks, or sleep on someone=E2=80=99s air mattress t=
o save a few dollars?=C2=A0
Outfit rightly calls out that it probably isn=E2=80=99t for most VCs. If yo=
u have more money than time, Outfit isn=E2=80=99t the solution for you. But=
 Outfit=E2=80=99s customer is most of the country. They are:=C2=A0
Low on Cash, High on Time. Chances are, they put their life savings into th=
e down payment on the home. They=E2=80=99re willing to spend the time to tu=
rn their investment into a home.
Used to Digital Experiences. They don=E2=80=99t want to deal with existing =
solutions, which are in-person, over-the-phone, and paper-based.=C2=A0
Willing to Pay for DIY as a Premium. The =E2=80=9CIKEA Effect [https://emai=
l.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OwyAMhU8TdoMwJCldsOim67lBRMBpmBKI-Jkotx-mXVSyZP=
tZ1qf3jC74iOlUe8yF1IxpclbByKUY-iuxqrcgB0lcnpaEuGnnVUkVyV5n74wuLobXB2N8IKta2=
GBGGJYFGAop9IVfeI_GCG5mbYGTf86kq3UYDCr8xXTGgMSrtZQ9d-LW8Xur4zjoOmeKtrZt0ab6=
crbp-4Pt-MDZ3XnMTQf4Ylegu12IU5xxBhwYiOEiJAUaf6Icg_RQn13Ptgenuc65aPOkJm4kqRD=
LHJMLj3Z-rnpD_zo0k1PrWw2unBMGPXu0b__lndjLTjl3VAGP7LEUTG-xhcJ7kDDKkTSajS278A=
H9Aejdf4E],=E2=80=9D from a 2011 HBS study in which people assign higher va=
lue to things that they created, shows customers willing to pay 63% more fo=
r DIY.=C2=A0
Early Outfit customers building their space
If you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring for a while, you might remember a=
 brilliant July guest post by native Texan Ali Montag [https://email.mg2.su=
bstack.com/c/eJxFUEuOhSAQPI0sjXxUXLCYzVzDgLTKiGCgmRdvP7znYpJOOt2VSn0WjbDFdK=
srZiQlQ5qdVXRgkvdiIlYJS2UvicvzmgBO7bzCVIBcxXi3aHQxfBhdx3qyq1EIvUoOK9Vg7WIGM=
RpquF2nyXAmevLWmXWxDsICCn4h3TEA8WpHvHLDvxr2XQdfDhFSu8SzXtq7-YwB9UacYh3rKKMd=
5f3IZUvb-BPlEKSn5WhEd26szcVk1MvxppOkQkQTkwtbhY9dn-A_QI0w132W4PCeIWjjwT7p8On=
jYxbvC1SAV_bwtvQ8a2QmqKSDHEhVs7E2E_6F_gCDnnY5] titled Monopolies and Magnol=
ias [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkN1uwyAMhZ-m3DXiJ6H0govd7DUiEtyUF=
UwEZlPefqyVNk3CQvaR_emc1RFsuRx2z5VYq1Dm4K3Q0qhpvDJvRy_MZFio860AJBeipdKA7W2J=
YXUUMj43OJcTu1vNzXKdrqDFzQu5KKlAmQv3QtyM9iDZD2d2zQfAFSx8QjkyAov2TrTXk3o7yff=
-MNOSS8BtqG2p5NbHsObUhb1Xypj3HAPUs0N_Tm7D3rnKgpVcciEFF2q6KDOIIX9ko9FE0R6nka=
dN_jvIiv0ldflxdwniU-j-5v6nhoGOGdAtEfzLOr3CejqhYweL8FUjEEF5DXsechRGaKNZp_ncY=
8M_0DfpEoAW]. She told the story of an American business empire that most o=
f us didn=E2=80=99t even know existed: Chip and Joanna Gaines=E2=80=99 Magn=
olia. Launched from the popularity of the couple=E2=80=99s hit HGTV show, F=
ixer Upper, Magnolia now spans DTC, retail, a luxury hotel, a construction =
business, a seven-city real estate agency, best-selling books, a campus wit=
h restaurants and a shopping center, and more than 20 million social follow=
ers, with a cable network on the way. Magnolia=E2=80=99s secret is this:=C2=
=A0
Magnolia is a monopoly because it serves an audience with few other excitin=
g options. Magnolia is about slowing down. It=E2=80=99s about watching the =
sunset and enjoying a plate of chocolate chip cookies with your family. It=
=E2=80=99s about using real, full fat butter. That=E2=80=99s a signal many =
American women are eager to open their pocketbooks to share. Lighting a $28=
 valencia orange scented candle from Magnolia sends a signal to houseguests=
, family members, and to yourself: Home is important.=C2=A0
She didn=E2=80=99t know it at the time, but Ali might as well have been wri=
ting about Outfit. It=E2=80=99s built for people for whom home is important=
, people Silicon Valley companies typically target only once they need to =
=E2=80=9Ccross the chasm,=E2=80=9D people who want nice things but want the=
m to be accessible and permanent, with some of their own elbow grease mixed=
 in.=C2=A0
But most of America drives pickup trucks -- the Ford F-Series has been the =
best-selling vehicle [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOwyAQRE8Tdrb4=
2IQsWMxmrmHxaSdMMFjQTOTbD04WIyEKVdPVrecMwj2XQ--5ImkVyhK8ZpIrMU834vXkmZoVCXV=
ZC8BmQtRYGpC92RicwZDTu4NSPpOHNhZWebPKrWLi1l45yBunVt68p8ClJOecxTQfIDnQ8AvlyA=
lI1A_EvV7E14V_9_N6vcZWDWZvjtHlrVsV-55dt_7_VGdK7cIpp10o6xc7X4-cvBlc-A1uQKjRD=
Fv2EAcxrLn4YR3YTLtVcdjz3qIpZ4gS4joL-k4hQZ-hjDPKxHwVamRj_slKJhVZe14mut35WJut=
aNzz3I4UnTLaXEK69_LzYTaI70LHtHTdWgp4LJCMjeA_BPHD_A0Ejx10gleNgAjlY3asfGKKSSV=
Jn-Zzp5_-B_0B-meT0g] in the US for decades -- and when they want to do home=
 improvements, they watch HGTV instead of calling the interior designer, an=
d head to Home Depot instead of paying someone to do it for them.=C2=A0
To learn more about how Outfit will reach its customers, its business model=
, Ian=E2=80=99s big vision, the risks, and the opportunity=E2=80=A6=20
If you=E2=80=99re an accredited investor and would like to learn more, you =
can apply to join the Not Boring Syndicate by clicking the button below. I=
=E2=80=99ll be sharing more details -- including deal terms and the deck --=
 over on AngelList.
Inspired to go give your kitchen that facelift you=E2=80=99ve been putting =
off? Join the waitlist here [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOhCAQ_=
Bq5jQFUhjlw2Mv-hkFolRXBQDMb_34ZPWzSSXeqH9VVRiMsMZ3qiBlJyZBGZxUTXHZD_yJW9ZbJ=
